  "prompt": "What colleges should I apply for with a percentile ranging between 50-60 in CAT mocks?",
  "response": "With a percentile range of 50-60 in your CAT mocks, you may want to consider aiming for colleges that have lower cutoffs and focus on programs that align with your academic background and interests. Here are some suggestions:\n\n### Tier 3 and Tier 4 B-Schools\n1. **Institute of Management Technology (IMT), Nagpur** - Offers a range of management programs with a moderate cutoff.\n2. **K. J. Somaiya Institute of Management Studies and Research, Mumbai** - Known for its management programs; check specific program cutoffs.\n3. **LBSIM, Delhi** - The cutoff is generally on the lower side for some of its programs.\n4. **Jagdish Sheth School of Management, Bangalore** - Offers diverse management courses.\n5. **Welingkar Institute of Management Development and Research, Mumbai** - Generally has a more inclusive cutoff.\n6. **Guljar Institute of Management & Technology (GIMT)** - A solid option for various PGDM courses.\n7. **Bharati Vidyapeeth Institute of Management and Entrepreneurship Development, Pune** - Offers good programs with moderate cutoffs.\n8. **Guru Gobind Singh Indraprastha University (GGSIPU), Delhi** - Various management programs with a lower percentile requirement.\n\n### State Universities & Colleges\n1. **Various State-level B-Schools** - Many state universities have their own management programs that may have cutoffs in your range.\n\n### Considerations\n- **Specialized Programs**: Some institutes offer niche courses or specializations that might be less competitive.\n- **Profile and Work Experience**: If you have strong extracurriculars, work experience, or a unique profile, it may help offset your mock scores.\n- **Backup Plans**: Consider applying to colleges offering alternative admission criteria like group discussions, personal interviews, or profile-based assessments.\n- **Retake CAT**: If you have the time, consider retaking the CAT with a solid preparation strategy to improve your score and expand your options.\n\n### Final Tips\n- Research each college's current admission criteria and cutoff trends as they can vary from year to year.\n- Attend webinars or open days of colleges to gain more insights.\n- Stay updated on new colleges or programs that may be offering options suitable for your profile.\n\nGood luck with your applications!",
